84
00:07:57,278 --> 00:08:01,840
<i>And he often spoke more fondly
of his nanny than he did of her.</i>

85
00:08:03,651 --> 00:08:06,449
He and Kathleen were adversaries.

86
00:08:06,520 --> 00:08:12,186
They couldn't help but be,
because Kathleen had very clear ideas...

87
00:08:12,259 --> 00:08:15,695
what she wanted,
what she expected of Chris.

88
00:08:15,763 --> 00:08:21,429
She wanted him to be a don--
a teacher-- and, uh--

89
00:08:21,502 --> 00:08:24,733
and that wasn't
his intention at all.

90
00:08:26,340 --> 00:08:30,071
<i>His father, Frank, was an officer
in the British army.</i>

91
00:08:32,146 --> 00:08:34,979
<i>And he was killed
in the First World War...</i>

92
00:08:35,049 --> 00:08:38,576
<i>when Chris was just a young boy.</i>

93
00:08:46,794 --> 00:08:51,288
<i>He later received a scholarship
to study history at Cambridge.</i>

94
00:08:51,365 --> 00:08:53,356
<i>But Chris was rebellious...</i>

95
00:08:53,434 --> 00:08:57,768
<i>and felt manipulated by the way
history was being taught at Cambridge.</i>

96
00:09:00,074 --> 00:09:02,167
<i>[Woman]
He did fine in his first year exams,</i>

97
00:09:02,242 --> 00:09:04,733
<i>and then in the second year,</i>

98
00:09:04,812 --> 00:09:08,304
<i>he deliberately wrote joke answers.</i>

99
00:09:08,382 --> 00:09:12,819
Wrote about the decoration of
the examining rooms, mocked the examiners.

100
00:09:12,886 --> 00:09:16,014
And shortly after wards,
he was called back to school from London,

101
00:09:16,090 --> 00:09:18,320
where he'd gone
for the summer holidays.

102
00:09:18,392 --> 00:09:23,193
<i>And got expelled,
because he wanted to be,</i>

103
00:09:23,263 --> 00:09:26,858
and I think because he wanted
to disappoint Kathleen...

104
00:09:26,934 --> 00:09:29,129
and make it perfectly clear...

105
00:09:29,203 --> 00:09:32,639
that he wasn't going to do her bidding.

106
00:09:32,706 --> 00:09:36,506
Isherwood was searching for a place
where he could live...

107
00:09:36,577 --> 00:09:40,206
and explore, I think,
among other things, his sexuality.

108
00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:42,680
He was beginning to realize
that he was gay.

109
00:09:44,318 --> 00:09:48,345
<i>England was a place
of confinement and strictures...</i>

110
00:09:48,422 --> 00:09:52,859
<i>that made it hard
fora gay man to pursue that life,</i>

111
00:09:52,926 --> 00:09:58,159
<i>if not openly, at least in a satisfying
and complete kind of way.</i>

112
00:10:04,738 --> 00:10:07,002
Also his very good friend, W. H. Auden,

113
00:10:07,074 --> 00:10:11,033
<i>one of the foremost poets
of the 20th century, had gone to Berlin.</i>

114
00:10:11,111 --> 00:10:16,845
<i>He was writing letters back to Isherwood,
urging him to come to Berlin.</i>

115
00:10:25,826 --> 00:10:28,590
<i>[Isherwood]
I was looking for a sort of homeland,</i>

116
00:10:28,662 --> 00:10:33,429
<i>for somewhere where I could function
in a way where I would feel freer...</i>

117
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:36,230
<i>than I felt in England
at that particular time...</i>

118
00:10:36,303 --> 00:10:38,567
<i>under the particular circumstances
I was living in.</i>

119
00:10:39,940 --> 00:10:41,931
<i>I think it was partly a class thing,</i>

120
00:10:42,009 --> 00:10:45,172
<i>but, of course, it was inextricably
mixed up with my homosexuality,</i>

121
00:10:45,245 --> 00:10:47,236
because, um,

122
00:10:47,314 --> 00:10:51,444
what I in fact started to encounter...

123
00:10:51,518 --> 00:10:54,544
was the German working class.

124
00:10:58,959 --> 00:11:03,055
<i>[York]
To Christopher, Berlin meant boys.</i>

125
00:11:05,432 --> 00:11:08,458
<i>At school, Christopher
had fallen in love with many boys...</i>

126
00:11:08,535 --> 00:11:11,800
<i>and been yearningly romantic
about them.</i>

127
00:11:11,872 --> 00:11:16,866
<i>At college, he had at last managed
to get into bed with one of them.</i>

128
00:11:16,944 --> 00:11:19,105
<i>Others experiences followed,</i>

129
00:11:19,179 --> 00:11:23,673
<i>all of them enjoyable,
but none entirely satisfying.</i>

130
00:11:23,750 --> 00:11:26,981
<i>This was because Christopher
was suffering from an inhibition...</i>

131
00:11:27,054 --> 00:11:30,490
<i>then not unusual
among upper-class homosexuals.</i>

132
00:11:30,557 --> 00:11:34,755
<i>He couldn't relax sexually
with a member of his own class or nation.</i>

133
00:11:36,330 --> 00:11:39,197
<i>He needed a working-class foreigner.</i>

134
00:11:41,668 --> 00:11:46,367
Isherwood just happened to be
at one of the most important spots to be in...

135
00:11:46,440 --> 00:11:48,431
in the 20th century.

136
00:11:48,509 --> 00:11:52,275
And that was in Germany
in the late 1920s, the early 1930s.

137
00:11:52,346 --> 00:11:56,783
<i>This was the place
in which Nazism was developing,</i>

138
00:11:56,850 --> 00:11:58,841
<i>emerging as an important force.</i>

139
00:11:58,919 --> 00:12:01,979
<i>This was where Hitler's Germany
was on the rise.</i>

140
00:12:04,458 --> 00:12:07,120
<i>[Bachardy]
Chris was observing everything
that was going on there...</i>

141
00:12:07,194 --> 00:12:09,185
<i>and formulating ideas...</i>

142
00:12:09,263 --> 00:12:13,791
<i>that would later go
into his two books about Berlin--</i>

143
00:12:13,867 --> 00:12:18,600
<i>one a novel
and the other a collection of stories--</i>

144
00:12:18,672 --> 00:12:21,641
<i>that really put him on the map
as an author.</i>

145
00:12:22,709 --> 00:12:28,306
<i>The success ofthose two books
led to a play,</i> I Am a Camera,

146
00:12:28,382 --> 00:12:32,910
<i>and a movie of the play
and eventually</i> Cabaret,

147
00:12:32,986 --> 00:12:36,217
which was quite
a success on Broadway,

148
00:12:36,290 --> 00:12:40,852
and then, of course,
the movie version with Liza Minnelli.

149
00:12:40,928 --> 00:12:46,560
<i>Ladies</i> und <i>Gents,
fraulein Sally Bowles!</i>

150
00:12:52,406 --> 00:12:55,136
Isherwood did not love
the way the movie was done.

151
00:12:55,208 --> 00:12:57,574
He thought
Liza Minnelli was too good.

152
00:12:57,644 --> 00:13:00,112
He made a funny comment
in interviews about, if--

153
00:13:00,180 --> 00:13:03,013
if she opens her mouth
and she's every bit Judy Garland's daughter...

154
00:13:03,083 --> 00:13:07,816
<i>and that there's no way a club in Berlin
could have housed such a talent.</i>

155
00:13:09,523 --> 00:13:11,514
♪ Life is a cabaret ♪

156
00:13:11,592 --> 00:13:15,619
<i>[Bachardy]
Five minutes after
Liza Minnelli had been on screen,</i>

157
00:13:15,696 --> 00:13:21,293
<i>Chris leaned towards me and said,
"She's no good. "[Laughs]</i>

158
00:13:21,368 --> 00:13:24,166
That's him.
[Laughing Continues]

159
00:13:24,237 --> 00:13:29,174
He liked Michael York very much.
He thought he was just right for it.

160
00:13:29,242 --> 00:13:32,268
But how could he like Liza Minnelli?

161
00:13:32,346 --> 00:13:35,110
Because, um--

162
00:13:35,182 --> 00:13:37,980
with her personality and talent,

163
00:13:38,051 --> 00:13:41,919
she destroyed
the character of Sally Bowles.

164
00:13:41,989 --> 00:13:47,621
Because if Sally Bowles isn't an amateur,
she isn't Sally Bowles.

165
00:13:47,694 --> 00:13:53,394
<i>I think Christopher Isherwood
enjoyed the film. I think he would say,</i>

166
00:13:53,467 --> 00:13:55,526
"Well, that's not what it was like."

167
00:13:55,602 --> 00:13:57,536
But it was a point of view.

168
00:13:57,604 --> 00:14:02,405
And when you write a piece,
you have to be prepared
for all kinds of points of view.

169
00:14:02,476 --> 00:14:06,003
And, um, he liked
that people liked it so much.

170
00:14:06,079 --> 00:14:10,539
<i>[Hodson]
Cabaret put him on the map
for the world at large,</i>

171
00:14:10,617 --> 00:14:12,949
<i>for the general public.</i>

172
00:14:13,020 --> 00:14:17,047
People who didn't read much
or may not have known
about Isherwood as an author--

173
00:14:17,124 --> 00:14:19,319
<i>Cabaret</i> was really the ticket to fame.</i>

174
00:14:19,393 --> 00:14:21,384
[Train Whistle Toots]

175
00:14:23,764 --> 00:14:28,428
<i>Isherwood had to leave Berlin in 1933,
as so many people did.</i>

176
00:14:28,502 --> 00:14:33,769
<i>And throughout the 1930s,
he'd wandered in Europe,</i>

177
00:14:33,840 --> 00:14:36,934
<i>looking for a country
where he could settle...</i>

178
00:14:37,010 --> 00:14:40,138
<i>with his German boyfriend,
Heinz Neddermeyer.</i>

179
00:14:42,249 --> 00:14:45,810
<i>There were problems
about passports, papers, visas.</i>

180
00:14:45,886 --> 00:14:49,845
<i>Heinz eventually was arrested
by the Gestapo...</i>

181
00:14:49,923 --> 00:14:53,484
<i>and first served a prison sentence
and then went into the army.</i>

182
00:14:55,228 --> 00:14:59,597
<i>This was very distressing.
This was a boy to whom, at the time,
he felt very committed.</i>

183
00:15:12,512 --> 00:15:14,503
<i>[Hodson]
I think for both Isherwood and Auden,</i>

184
00:15:14,581 --> 00:15:19,814
<i>they could see that there was
a war on the horizon in Europe,
without any doubt at all.</i>

185
00:15:19,886 --> 00:15:23,822
And they recognized that they had no part
in that, because they were pacifists.

186
00:15:25,459 --> 00:15:28,087
<i>So he and Auden turned
their backs on Europe.</i>

187
00:15:28,161 --> 00:15:31,289
<i>They decided to emigrate
to the United States.</i>

188
00:15:31,364 --> 00:15:36,996
<i>And they arrived in New York City
in January, 1939.</i>

189
00:15:42,843 --> 00:15:47,246
<i>[Bachardy]
Chris didn't like the cold.
He didn't like the grime of New York.</i>

190
00:15:47,314 --> 00:15:51,717
He didn't like the bustle,
and he longed for the West.

191
00:15:53,120 --> 00:15:56,715
<i>He had a romantic vision of the West,</i>

192
00:15:56,790 --> 00:16:01,022
<i>which he got from John Ford movies.</i>

193
00:16:01,094 --> 00:16:03,790
<i>[Hodson]
So he headed out across country...</i>

194
00:16:03,864 --> 00:16:07,231
<i>and ended up in Southern California.</i>

195
00:16:16,676 --> 00:16:20,442
<i>Los Angeles offered a tremendously
varied cultural atmosphere...</i>

196
00:16:20,514 --> 00:16:24,382
<i>for someone like Isherwood
to drop into the center.</i>

197
00:16:24,451 --> 00:16:26,919
<i>There were the expatriates,</i>

198
00:16:26,987 --> 00:16:31,321
<i>the artists, the musicians,
the actors, the directors--</i>

199
00:16:31,391 --> 00:16:33,382
<i>a great boiling pot...</i>

200
00:16:33,460 --> 00:16:38,557
<i>for all sorts of cultural
and artistic life and creativity.</i>

201
00:16:38,632 --> 00:16:41,123
<i>He fit in beautifully.</i>

202
00:16:41,201 --> 00:16:45,069
<i>Because he had something to offer,
they had something to offer him.</i>

203
00:16:46,673 --> 00:16:48,698
He's one of the few writers
who will admit...

204
00:16:48,775 --> 00:16:51,073
that writing for Hollywood
made him a better writer.

205
00:16:51,144 --> 00:16:55,638
<i>He learned an economy of  language.
He learned how to use dialogue,</i>

206
00:16:55,715 --> 00:16:58,650
<i>how to set something up visually
in a paragraph...</i>

207
00:16:58,718 --> 00:17:01,653
<i>rather than in pages and pages.</i>

208
00:17:01,721 --> 00:17:03,712
When he abandoned England...

209
00:17:03,790 --> 00:17:07,351
and came to this place
where there were no rules,

210
00:17:07,427 --> 00:17:12,763
<i>he also abandoned
the methodology...</i>

211
00:17:12,833 --> 00:17:18,362
<i>and structures and styles
of traditional novel writing.</i>

212
00:17:18,438 --> 00:17:22,067
<i>He wrote with this camera eye,
if you like,</i>

213
00:17:22,142 --> 00:17:24,167
<i>influenced by the cinema.</i>

214
00:17:33,019 --> 00:17:36,284
<i>[York As Isherwood]
I am a camera with its shutter open,</i>

215
00:17:36,356 --> 00:17:39,883
<i>quite passive,
recording, not thinking.</i>

216
00:17:42,128 --> 00:17:45,461
<i>Someday, all this will
have to be developed,</i>

217
00:17:45,532 --> 00:17:48,729
<i>carefully printed, fixed.</i>

218
00:17:54,140 --> 00:17:58,577
Pulling up roots from England,
coming to this country,

219
00:17:58,645 --> 00:18:01,705
was an outward manifestation...

220
00:18:01,781 --> 00:18:05,342
<i>of a spiritual crisis in his life.</i>

221
00:18:07,187 --> 00:18:10,816
<i>The impending war
was getting him down,</i>

222
00:18:10,891 --> 00:18:15,351
<i>and he really was in need
of some kind of guidance.</i>

223
00:18:17,464 --> 00:18:20,900
And he certainly couldn't have got it
from the Church of England,

224
00:18:20,967 --> 00:18:25,267
because he'd learned to, uh, loathe...

225
00:18:25,338 --> 00:18:28,000
all that official religion in England.

226
00:18:29,009 --> 00:18:31,000
<i>[Man]
He met Aldous Huxley,</i>

227
00:18:31,077 --> 00:18:34,342
<i>who in turn introduced him
to Swami Prabhavananda,</i>

228
00:18:34,414 --> 00:18:37,645
who had started the Vedanta Society
in Southern California.

229
00:18:37,717 --> 00:18:41,483
And Isherwood studied Vedanta,
a branch of Hindu philosophy,

230
00:18:41,554 --> 00:18:45,217
with Prabhavananda,
for the rest of his life, really.

231
00:18:47,027 --> 00:18:50,588
Chris immediately told him
he was homosexual,

232
00:18:50,664 --> 00:18:53,224
<i>and Prabhavananda didn't regard that...</i>

233
00:18:53,300 --> 00:18:56,701
<i>as an insurmountable obstacle.</i>

234
00:18:58,104 --> 00:19:02,700
<i>He became such a devout follower
of Vedanta and of the Swami...</i>

235
00:19:02,776 --> 00:19:04,801
that he did seriously
consider becoming a monk.

236
00:19:04,878 --> 00:19:08,245
<i>But there were two things
that stopped him.</i>

237
00:19:08,315 --> 00:19:11,807
<i>He recognized in himself
that he wanted to have...</i>

238
00:19:11,885 --> 00:19:17,050
a longtime personal commitment
to a serious relationship with a partner.

239
00:19:17,123 --> 00:19:21,150
<i>The second thing he knew
is that he needed to continue writing,</i>

240
00:19:21,227 --> 00:19:23,252
<i>that he could not give that up.</i>

241
00:20:22,956 --> 00:20:26,585
Um, these are
my mother's own scrapbooks.

242
00:20:26,659 --> 00:20:28,650
Um--

243
00:20:30,230 --> 00:20:32,858
Joan Bennett, um--

244
00:20:34,367 --> 00:20:36,733
<i>I think this is Nancy Carroll.</i>

245
00:20:37,804 --> 00:20:41,035
Oh, Louise Brooks.
She had Louise Brooks here.

246
00:20:46,079 --> 00:20:48,206
<i>Look at the trouble.
It's beautifully done.</i>

247
00:20:48,281 --> 00:20:51,148
<i>How carefully all these things
are put in.</i>

248
00:20:51,217 --> 00:20:54,084
<i>Imagine cutting out that so carefully.</i>

249
00:20:55,321 --> 00:20:59,417
<i>I must get my orderliness
from my mother.</i>

250
00:21:05,799 --> 00:21:10,361
<i>My parents were attracted
to the glamour of Hollywood,</i>

251
00:21:10,437 --> 00:21:14,931
<i>especially my mother,
who loved movies and movie stars.</i>

252
00:21:16,709 --> 00:21:21,874
<i>So as soon as they were married,
they traveled across country by car...</i>

253
00:21:21,948 --> 00:21:24,917
<i>and settled in Los Angeles.</i>

254
00:21:24,984 --> 00:21:28,442
<i>And soon my mother gave birth
to my brother Ted.</i>

255
00:21:29,522 --> 00:21:33,083
<i>I was born four years later in 1934..</i>

256
00:21:38,131 --> 00:21:41,726
<i>It was during World War II
when we were growing up,</i>

257
00:21:43,470 --> 00:21:48,237
<i>and there was a big demand
on my father to work long hours,</i>

258
00:21:48,308 --> 00:21:50,936
<i>because he worked
in the aerospace industry.</i>

259
00:21:51,010 --> 00:21:55,413
<i>So while my father
was working overtime,</i>

260
00:21:55,482 --> 00:22:01,045
<i>my mother would take Ted and me
downtown by streetcar to the movies.</i>

261
00:22:36,256 --> 00:22:40,022
This is one of the key theaters
I remember.

262
00:22:40,093 --> 00:22:43,722
I think it's the first one
I remember being brought to--

263
00:22:43,796 --> 00:22:47,630
to see a Joan Crawford movie
called <i>My Shining Hour</i>.

264
00:22:47,700 --> 00:22:49,998
Um, I was four.

265
00:22:57,143 --> 00:22:59,941
<i>[Man]
His mother would take his brother
out of school even,</i>

266
00:23:00,013 --> 00:23:02,948
<i>and they would go to movies
during the day.</i>

267
00:23:03,016 --> 00:23:06,247
<i>Then Don would even go on his own.
When he was--</i>

268
00:23:06,319 --> 00:23:08,378
When he was very young, he would go.

269
00:23:08,454 --> 00:23:10,445
He wasn't old enough
to actually get a ticket,

270
00:23:10,523 --> 00:23:14,152
<i>and he would get someone to buy the ticket
for him to get into the theater.</i>

271
00:23:14,227 --> 00:23:19,790
<i>At the theater, he was looking up close
at these big images of these movie stars.</i>

272
00:23:35,949 --> 00:23:38,474
[Laughing]

273
00:23:38,551 --> 00:23:41,884
<i>[Bachardy]
We started as ordinary fans,</i>

274
00:23:41,955 --> 00:23:46,517
<i>sitting in the bleachers
outside the theater with our mother.</i>

275
00:23:46,593 --> 00:23:50,290
<i>And eventually,
Ted and I had the idea--</i>

276
00:23:50,363 --> 00:23:52,388
<i>when going to a premiere--</i>

277
00:23:52,465 --> 00:23:57,425
<i>to put on our best jacket
and trousers and ties...</i>

278
00:23:57,503 --> 00:24:00,700
<i>and try to look as though
we belonged there.</i>

279
00:24:08,615 --> 00:24:12,210
<i>And we also brought our camera with us,</i>

280
00:24:12,285 --> 00:24:17,917
<i>and we started taking pictures
of ourselves with the movie stars.</i>

281
00:24:34,974 --> 00:24:38,774
<i>[Woman]
I met Don Bachardy all by himself.</i>

282
00:24:38,845 --> 00:24:42,246
Round cheeks and bright eyes.

283
00:24:42,315 --> 00:24:47,981
And he was one of those young kids
who would ask you to sign an autograph,

284
00:24:48,054 --> 00:24:52,787
come next to you and--while you sign--
and his friend would take the picture.

285
00:24:52,859 --> 00:24:57,956
<i>And years and years later, he found
the photograph and gave me a copy of it,</i>

286
00:24:58,031 --> 00:25:00,659
<i>which is wonderful.</i>

287
00:25:16,115 --> 00:25:19,141
<i>[Bachardy]
Ted and I went to the beach every weekend.</i>

288
00:25:19,218 --> 00:25:22,517
<i>Ted mysteriously at first...</i>

289
00:25:22,588 --> 00:25:27,548
<i>always wanted to walk us
about a mile and a half...</i>

290
00:25:27,627 --> 00:25:30,494
<i>to Will Rogers State Beach...</i>

291
00:25:30,563 --> 00:25:33,964
<i>for us to lay out our beach blanket.</i>

292
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:41,940
<i>I soon discovered that that was because
it was the queer beach in Santa Monica.</i>

293
00:25:46,245 --> 00:25:50,204
<i>This is more or less the area of the beach...</i>

294
00:25:50,283 --> 00:25:52,774
where I met Chris,

295
00:25:52,852 --> 00:25:57,880
and that would have been
when I was probably 16.

296
00:26:01,694 --> 00:26:03,685
<i>He was so friendly.</i>

297
00:26:03,763 --> 00:26:08,860
<i>He had such a charming smile
and sparkling eyes.</i>

298
00:26:08,935 --> 00:26:11,426
Eyes that had such energy.

299
00:26:11,504 --> 00:26:14,064
Eyes that ate you up.

300
00:26:15,441 --> 00:26:20,674
<i>Sometimes Chris and I would just
wave to each other in the distance.</i>

301
00:26:22,482 --> 00:26:26,543
<i>And sometimes he would
come up to our blanket...</i>

302
00:26:26,619 --> 00:26:30,248
<i>and engage us in conversation.</i>

303
00:26:30,323 --> 00:26:35,260
<i>A t that time, I was only interested
in actors and actresses.</i>

304
00:26:35,328 --> 00:26:39,662
<i>Writers were
an unknown quantity to me.</i>

305
00:26:41,401 --> 00:26:43,995
<i>So I wasn't impressed by Chris as a writer.</i>

306
00:26:44,070 --> 00:26:49,531
<i>And at the time, he was really
only interested in my brother Ted.</i>

307
00:26:49,609 --> 00:26:52,271
<i>I knew they had slept together
a couple of times.</i>

308
00:26:54,647 --> 00:26:58,014
[Men Laughing, Chattering]

309
00:26:58,084 --> 00:27:03,750
<i>The first time I can say
that I met Chris socially...</i>

310
00:27:03,823 --> 00:27:09,420
<i>was in October of 1952
when I was 18.</i>

311
00:27:11,030 --> 00:27:14,158
Ted and I
were invited for drinks...

312
00:27:14,233 --> 00:27:19,569
by a couple of, uh,
queer men we knew.

313
00:27:21,007 --> 00:27:24,738
<i>And they'd had Chris for dinner.</i>

314
00:27:26,112 --> 00:27:31,243
<i>And I think Ted and I
were invited for dessert.
[Laughing]</i>

315
00:27:33,853 --> 00:27:36,481
Dessert for them and for Chris.

316
00:27:42,562 --> 00:27:46,157
<i>It was one of the first times
that I got drunk,</i>

317
00:27:46,232 --> 00:27:50,293
<i>and I was very unused to drinking
and had too much to drink.</i>

318
00:27:50,369 --> 00:27:53,805
<i>And Chris had been there
since before dinner,</i>

319
00:27:53,873 --> 00:27:57,400
<i>so he was fairly drunk too.</i>

320
00:27:57,477 --> 00:28:01,811
<i>And we found ourselves standing up
in the dining room, kissing.</i>

321
00:28:05,551 --> 00:28:09,009
<i>We lost our balance
and fell against a big window,</i>

322
00:28:09,088 --> 00:28:12,023
<i>which was all panes of glass--
[Glass Breaking]</i>

323
00:28:12,091 --> 00:28:16,528
<i>and we broke one of the glass panes.</i>

324
00:28:16,596 --> 00:28:21,693
<i>That sound of glass breaking
brought me out of my alcoholic haze,</i>

325
00:28:21,767 --> 00:28:25,168
<i>and I suddenly said
I had to go home.</i>

326
00:28:29,942 --> 00:28:35,005
<i>I didn't see Chris again
until the following February.</i>

327
00:28:38,351 --> 00:28:41,445
<i>We were going to the beach
when, in the middle of the drive,</i>

328
00:28:41,521 --> 00:28:45,514
<i>Ted said,
"Why don't we stop and see Chris?"</i>

329
00:28:46,959 --> 00:28:50,451
<i>He was in the middle of work
when Ted and I arrived.</i>

330
00:28:54,233 --> 00:28:57,600
<i>I remember he made us scrambled eggs,</i>

331
00:28:57,670 --> 00:29:00,161
<i>with mushrooms from a can.</i>

332
00:29:00,239 --> 00:29:03,606
<i>Mushrooms were one of the few things...</i>

333
00:29:03,676 --> 00:29:06,668
<i>I found disgusting to eat,</i>

334
00:29:06,746 --> 00:29:09,738
<i>particularly ones from a can.</i>

335
00:29:12,852 --> 00:29:16,481
<i>I didn't much like
the breakfast he prepared,</i>

336
00:29:16,556 --> 00:29:18,820
<i>but I did like Chris.</i>

337
00:29:27,466 --> 00:29:30,560
<i>Our morning encounter
was such a success...</i>

338
00:29:30,636 --> 00:29:34,538
<i>that Chris decided to come
to the beach with Ted and me.</i>

339
00:29:41,581 --> 00:29:44,550
<i>When we parted
at the end of the evening,</i>

340
00:29:44,617 --> 00:29:49,919
<i>we made plans to do the same thing
the following weekend.</i>

341
00:29:49,989 --> 00:29:54,449
<i>And the following weekend
provided the first night...</i>

342
00:29:54,527 --> 00:29:58,054
<i>Chris and I spent alone together.</i>

343
00:30:20,386 --> 00:30:24,982
[Beeping]

344
00:30:26,926 --> 00:30:28,917
Ted?

345
00:30:28,995 --> 00:30:33,261
Uh, I'm nearly dressed.
Are you ready?

346
00:30:33,332 --> 00:30:35,527
The film goes on at 1:00.

347
00:30:35,601 --> 00:30:39,298
So I'll pick you up in half an hour?

348
00:30:39,372 --> 00:30:41,897
Okay. Bye-bye.

349
00:30:49,849 --> 00:30:54,582
<i>Not long after that first night
Chris and I spent together,</i>

350
00:30:54,654 --> 00:30:58,954
<i>Ted began to go into another
of his nervous breakdowns.</i>

351
00:31:01,527 --> 00:31:05,725
<i>They'd begun
when he was 15 and I was 11.</i>

352
00:31:05,798 --> 00:31:08,323
<i>This was maybe the third one.</i>

353
00:31:10,636 --> 00:31:13,901
<i>Of course it was devastating for me,</i>

354
00:31:13,973 --> 00:31:18,342
<i>because he was really the key person
in my life at the time.</i>

355
00:31:18,411 --> 00:31:22,006
<i>And suddenly
he wasn't available to me.</i>

356
00:31:23,883 --> 00:31:27,819
<i>[Man Muttering, Groaning]</i>

357
00:31:27,887 --> 00:31:32,415
<i>He had several series
of shock treatments.</i>

358
00:31:32,491 --> 00:31:37,224
<i>That was the standard therapy
in the '50s,</i>

359
00:31:37,296 --> 00:31:41,027
<i>which permanently
changed him, I think.</i>

360
00:31:42,234 --> 00:31:45,067
<i>[Electrical Buzzing]
[Groaning]</i>

361
00:31:49,075 --> 00:31:51,066
<i>Chris was concerned about me,</i>

362
00:31:51,143 --> 00:31:55,477
<i>because he guessed
how important Ted was to me.</i>

363
00:31:55,548 --> 00:31:59,382
<i>And he started
asking me out to dinner,</i>

364
00:31:59,452 --> 00:32:02,387
<i>the ballet and the theater,</i>

365
00:32:02,455 --> 00:32:05,083
<i>Just as a means of showing support.</i>

366
00:32:09,995 --> 00:32:12,987
<i>[York As Isherwood]
I feel a special kind of love for Don.</i>

367
00:32:16,102 --> 00:32:18,502
<i>I suppose I'm just
another frustrated father.</i>

368
00:32:18,571 --> 00:32:23,031
<i>But this feeling exists
at a very deep level,</i>

369
00:32:23,109 --> 00:32:26,601
<i>beneath names for things
or their appearances.</i>

370
00:32:26,679 --> 00:32:30,547
<i>We're just back from a trip
to Palm Springs together,</i>

371
00:32:30,616 --> 00:32:34,950
<i>which was one of those rare experiences
of nearly pure joy.</i>

372
00:32:37,690 --> 00:32:41,387
<i>There's a brilliant wide-openness
about his mouse-face,</i>

373
00:32:41,460 --> 00:32:45,157
<i>with its brown eyes and tooth-gap
and bristling crew cut,</i>

374
00:32:45,231 --> 00:32:48,132
<i>which affects everybody who sees him.</i>

375
00:32:48,200 --> 00:32:53,194
<i>If one could still be like that at 40,
one would be a saint.</i>

376
00:32:59,512 --> 00:33:03,175
<i>[Bachardy]
The official mental diagnosis for Ted...</i>

377
00:33:03,249 --> 00:33:06,912
<i>was a manic-depressive schizophrenic,</i>

378
00:33:06,986 --> 00:33:10,183
<i>and, indeed, he fills the bill.</i>

379
00:33:14,226 --> 00:33:19,858
<i>He's being medicated by the people
who run the building he lives in.</i>

380
00:33:19,932 --> 00:33:22,594
<i>You know, if he gets too obstreperous,</i>

381
00:33:22,668 --> 00:33:26,160
<i>um, they medicate him down.</i>

382
00:33:26,238 --> 00:33:27,865
<i>Hi.
[Ted]
Hi.</i>

383
00:33:27,940 --> 00:33:30,875
<i>Guido's here with me.
You're right on time.</i>

384
00:33:30,943 --> 00:33:33,002
He's filming.

385
00:33:33,078 --> 00:33:38,880
<i>I never know quite
what state he's going to be in.</i>

386
00:33:42,588 --> 00:33:44,783
You know who Josh Hartnett is?

387
00:33:44,857 --> 00:33:47,325
Of course.
We've seen his movies together.

388
00:33:47,393 --> 00:33:49,554
[TV]
Here we come.
Oh, is that he?

389
00:33:49,628 --> 00:33:52,188
Yeah.

390
00:33:52,264 --> 00:33:55,529
Look at all of 'em.

391
00:33:55,601 --> 00:33:58,399
Oh, that's
a great picture of him.

392
00:33:58,470 --> 00:34:01,337
Yeah, that's just terrific.

393
00:34:01,407 --> 00:34:03,500
Charlize Theron.

394
00:34:03,576 --> 00:34:06,477
Uh, yeah. Well, you know
what I think of her.

395
00:34:06,545 --> 00:34:09,708
You don't like her.
You know I don't.

396
00:34:09,782 --> 00:34:12,148
I don't dislike her.
I'm just not interested in her.

397
00:34:12,218 --> 00:34:15,051
I don't understand
why you don't think she's pretty.

398
00:34:15,120 --> 00:34:18,317
<i>Um, pretty in a kind
of vacuous way.</i>

399
00:34:23,562 --> 00:34:29,330
<i>And he's still, at 75,
having manic phases.</i>

400
00:34:29,401 --> 00:34:31,494
<i>I know right away...</i>

401
00:34:31,570 --> 00:34:35,438
<i>when he's going
into his other persona.</i>

402
00:34:37,309 --> 00:34:39,402
<i>It really wrecked his life.</i>

403
00:34:44,083 --> 00:34:47,541
<i>[Man Narrating]
Yes, this is the land of the rainbow's end,</i>

404
00:34:47,620 --> 00:34:50,418
<i>where out door pageantry
enraptures the soul.</i>

405
00:34:50,489 --> 00:34:54,186
<i>[Bucknell]
In the early '50s
when Don and Chris first met,</i>

406
00:34:54,260 --> 00:34:59,391
<i>obviously it was, let's say,
a squarer time than now, even in California.</i>

407
00:34:59,465 --> 00:35:03,424
Isherwood had just done over
and moved into
a lovely little garden house...

408
00:35:03,502 --> 00:35:07,666
<i>on the property
of his close friend, Evelyn Hooker.</i>

409
00:35:07,740 --> 00:35:10,334
<i>She was a psychologist...</i>

410
00:35:10,409 --> 00:35:14,436
<i>who spent most of her career
studying the gay community in Los Angeles,</i>

411
00:35:14,513 --> 00:35:16,504
<i>and she published
the first research suggesting...</i>

412
00:35:16,582 --> 00:35:21,485
<i>that homosexuals were as well-adjusted
psychologically as heterosexuals.</i>

413
00:35:23,355 --> 00:35:27,291
Even Evelyn Hooker and her husband,
who were pretty liberal-minded--

414
00:35:27,359 --> 00:35:33,195
and obviously she was engaged
in studying the behavior of gay people--
didn't feel comfortable...

415
00:35:33,265 --> 00:35:38,567
<i>when this very young-looking boy
moved into their garden house.</i>

416
00:35:38,637 --> 00:35:41,435
<i>They said to Isherwood
that it couldn't go on.</i>

417
00:35:43,375 --> 00:35:45,434
<i>Isherwood decided
that he would move out.</i>

418
00:35:45,511 --> 00:35:48,139
<i>Don was more important to him
than the garden house.</i>

419
00:35:48,213 --> 00:35:51,478
<i>- They found another place to live.
- [Vehicle Engine Starts]</i>

420
00:35:56,922 --> 00:36:01,689
<i>[Bachardy]
Our honeymoon trip was on
my Easter vacation from college.</i>

421
00:36:01,760 --> 00:36:04,729
<i>Chris was waiting for me
on the street outside.</i>

422
00:36:05,965 --> 00:36:09,628
<i>His plan was to drive us
to Monument Valley.</i>

423
00:36:11,403 --> 00:36:14,338
He was sitting in the sun
and smiling at me.

424
00:36:14,406 --> 00:36:19,639
And, um, I was so pleased
to step into the passenger seat.

425
00:36:19,712 --> 00:36:22,374
<i>And we drove off right then.</i>

426
00:36:22,448 --> 00:36:25,884
<i>There weren't even roads
into Monument Valley then.</i>

427
00:36:25,951 --> 00:36:28,681
<i>Paved roads didn't exist.</i>

428
00:36:30,589 --> 00:36:34,855
<i>But we made it.
We arrived in this bunkhouse.</i>

429
00:36:37,196 --> 00:36:39,289
<i>Nothing but men sitting...</i>

430
00:36:39,365 --> 00:36:43,324
<i>at this ranch-type table,</i>

431
00:36:43,402 --> 00:36:47,998
<i>at the head of which was John Ford,
and it was all his crewmen.</i>

432
00:36:48,073 --> 00:36:52,874
And, of course,
they all  had to be, um, macho types.

433
00:36:54,113 --> 00:36:58,049
<i>And here were
this small Englishman...</i>

434
00:36:58,117 --> 00:37:02,816
<i>and his very
young-looking boyfriend.</i>

435
00:37:02,888 --> 00:37:07,052
<i>And maybe they assumed
we were father and son.</i>

436
00:37:09,962 --> 00:37:13,329
[Ship Whistle Blows]

437
00:37:16,068 --> 00:37:21,734
<i>[York As Isherwood] Yesterday at noon
when the great ship thundered good-bye
to the echoing towers of Manhattan,</i>

438
00:37:21,807 --> 00:37:24,571
<i>I could hardly hold back my tears.</i>

439
00:37:24,643 --> 00:37:26,634
<i>It was so beautiful.</i>

440
00:37:28,313 --> 00:37:31,077
<i>The Hudson full off us sing tugboats...</i>

441
00:37:31,150 --> 00:37:34,313
<i>and brimming with silver light.</i>

442
00:37:34,386 --> 00:37:38,413
<i>The thought
that it was Don's first voyage,</i>

443
00:37:38,490 --> 00:37:42,051
<i>never to be quite duplicated for him--</i>

444
00:37:46,899 --> 00:37:50,198
<i>[Bachardy]
Chris and I were making our first trip...</i>

445
00:37:50,269 --> 00:37:53,363
<i>to Europe together,</i>

446
00:37:53,439 --> 00:37:56,067
uh, in 1956...

447
00:37:56,141 --> 00:38:01,704
<i>when I was 21 and he was 51.</i>

448
00:38:06,285 --> 00:38:08,549
<i>We were on an Italian ship,</i>

449
00:38:08,620 --> 00:38:12,147
<i>and it docked at Gibraltar.</i>

450
00:38:14,159 --> 00:38:19,791
<i>It occurred to Chris that,
Gibraltar being so near to Tangier,</i>

451
00:38:19,865 --> 00:38:22,732
<i>we might get off the ship
for a weekend...</i>

452
00:38:24,603 --> 00:38:29,597
<i>and pop around to Tangier
and see Paul Bowles.</i>

453
00:38:36,849 --> 00:38:40,114
<i>I never had any drugs in my life.</i>

454
00:38:40,185 --> 00:38:42,983
<i>I simply didn't know what I was in for.</i>

455
00:38:43,055 --> 00:38:46,354
And here we were, uh-- um--

456
00:38:46,425 --> 00:38:51,089
uh, smoking the finest keif...

457
00:38:51,163 --> 00:38:55,224
and eating majoon.

458
00:38:55,300 --> 00:38:57,291
It was so delicious.

459
00:38:57,369 --> 00:39:02,432
Oh! Little did we know
what we were in for.

460
00:39:05,677 --> 00:39:11,274
<i>We were offered the hashish
in a very elaborate pipe...</i>

461
00:39:11,350 --> 00:39:15,912
<i>with all kinds of bangles
coming down from it,</i>

462
00:39:15,988 --> 00:39:21,119
<i>and it seemed very exotic
and mysterious.</i>

463
00:39:28,033 --> 00:39:32,163
<i>It took us both a long time
to have any reaction.</i>

464
00:39:34,673 --> 00:39:36,664
<i>And then little by little...</i>

465
00:39:36,742 --> 00:39:40,906
<i>I began to get very scared
and very paranoid.</i>

466
00:39:43,382 --> 00:39:49,287
<i>Paul Bowles suddenly seemed to me
a very sinister character.</i>

467
00:39:49,354 --> 00:39:52,448
<i>I felt that there was
a situation developing...</i>

468
00:39:52,524 --> 00:39:55,425
<i>in which Paul was trying...</i>

469
00:39:55,494 --> 00:39:59,123
<i>to isolate me from Chris.</i>

470
00:39:59,198 --> 00:40:03,658
And I said to Chris--
[Whispers]
"We've got to get out of here."

471
00:40:05,737 --> 00:40:08,001
<i>We got to our hotel,</i>

472
00:40:08,073 --> 00:40:13,010
<i>and by that time, I was really
deep into the experience...</i>

473
00:40:13,078 --> 00:40:18,812
<i>and scared like I'd never been
before in my life.</i>

474
00:40:18,884 --> 00:40:22,012
<i>This was real, real terror.</i>

475
00:40:25,123 --> 00:40:27,353
<i>I thought I was insane...</i>

476
00:40:27,426 --> 00:40:31,920
<i>and that I would never find
my way back to sanity.</i>

477
00:40:33,098 --> 00:40:36,033
I thought, "Ah, I'm like Ted.

478
00:40:36,101 --> 00:40:40,470
I'm going down the same drain."

479
00:40:40,539 --> 00:40:44,339
And I was just scared out of my wits.

480
00:40:44,409 --> 00:40:46,707
And I know that Chris was scared too.

481
00:40:46,778 --> 00:40:50,179
<i>But he never left my side.</i>

482
00:40:50,249 --> 00:40:53,685
<i>He never stopped reassuring me.</i>

483
00:40:55,187 --> 00:41:00,250
<i>We were clinging
to each other for dear life.</i>

484
00:41:04,630 --> 00:41:09,192
<i>[York As Isherwood]
I now realize what I should have known
from the start--</i>

485
00:41:09,268 --> 00:41:13,500
<i>that I ought never to have
let Don take the stuff,</i>

486
00:41:13,572 --> 00:41:18,271
<i>because the whole Ted problem
now came up to the surface.</i>

487
00:41:18,343 --> 00:41:21,801
<i>And yet, in another way,
it was good that he did take it,</i>

488
00:41:21,880 --> 00:41:24,872
<i>because he passed
through the experience...</i>

489
00:41:24,950 --> 00:41:27,441
<i>and, to some degree, overcame it.</i>

490
00:41:28,854 --> 00:41:34,417
<i>I feel that a new and very strong bond
exists between Don and myself.</i>

491
00:41:34,493 --> 00:41:38,429
<i>This is a tremendous
experience we've shared.</i>

492
00:41:44,703 --> 00:41:50,664
<i>[Bachardy]
I think we crossed a barrier for the first time
and really became trustful...</i>

493
00:41:50,742 --> 00:41:53,472
<i>and sure of each other...</i>

494
00:41:53,545 --> 00:41:57,447
<i>in a way that we hadn't been before.</i>

495
00:42:19,204 --> 00:42:22,571
<i>[Bell Tolling]</i>

496
00:42:25,711 --> 00:42:31,047
Well, Don as a man
was entirely formed by Chris.

497
00:42:31,116 --> 00:42:34,608
And I can't remember
what his accent was...

498
00:42:34,686 --> 00:42:37,553
or his voice was like
when he was a young boy.

499
00:42:37,622 --> 00:42:42,821
<i>But he came to have the same voice
and the same accent and mannerisms...</i>

500
00:42:42,894 --> 00:42:46,159
<i>as if he'd been raised in Oxford.</i>

501
00:42:47,499 --> 00:42:52,527
<i>Isherwood had succeeded
in cloning himself in some curious way,</i>

502
00:42:52,604 --> 00:42:57,701
because their mannerisms,
their speech patterns were so similar.

503
00:42:57,776 --> 00:43:02,179
<i>I had the impression that Don
had actually gained access...</i>

504
00:43:02,247 --> 00:43:05,045
<i>to Chris's genetic code...</i>

505
00:43:05,117 --> 00:43:08,678
<i>and had gobbled it up
and reproduced himself.</i>

506
00:43:09,955 --> 00:43:13,152
Before we went out anywhere,
I remember very clearly...

507
00:43:13,225 --> 00:43:15,693
<i>I would always show him
what I was wearing...</i>

508
00:43:15,761 --> 00:43:18,229
<i>and say, "What do you think?
Is this right?"</i>

509
00:43:18,296 --> 00:43:22,289
<i>And if he said, "Oh, I think
another jacket or another tie"...</i>

510
00:43:22,367 --> 00:43:24,733
<i>or maybe a whole other ensemble,</i>

511
00:43:24,803 --> 00:43:26,737
<i>I would change.</i>

512
00:43:26,805 --> 00:43:31,572
<i>Don had this British accent,
and we're both Los Angeles boys.</i>

513
00:43:31,643 --> 00:43:34,373
Don should essentially
be talking like I talk.

514
00:43:34,446 --> 00:43:37,574
I'm from Montebello.
He's from Glendale.

515
00:43:37,649 --> 00:43:39,640
Really Atwater, I know.

516
00:43:39,718 --> 00:43:44,178
And I never spoke to him about it,
but it's very noticeable.

517
00:43:44,256 --> 00:43:47,657
And I've heard people say,
"Where did you grow up in England?"

518
00:43:47,726 --> 00:43:50,194
And he always said,
"No, I'm from Los Angeles."

519
00:43:55,400 --> 00:44:00,030
<i>[Bachardy]
The English accent showed up
after less than a year.</i>

520
00:44:00,105 --> 00:44:04,132
<i>People who knew me before
thought I was putting on the dog,</i>

521
00:44:04,209 --> 00:44:06,541
<i>giving myself airs.</i>

522
00:44:06,611 --> 00:44:11,810
<i>I couldn't help it.
I'm an unconscious impersonator.</i>

523
00:44:16,188 --> 00:44:20,625
<i>Chris said how important it was
to stand up straight,</i>

524
00:44:20,692 --> 00:44:22,990
<i>hold my head up.</i>

525
00:44:23,061 --> 00:44:27,054
<i>And he gave me as an example...</i>

526
00:44:27,132 --> 00:44:31,228
<i>a young revolutionary
on his way to the gallows.</i>

527
00:44:31,303 --> 00:44:35,797
<i>The whole town was watching,</i>

528
00:44:35,874 --> 00:44:40,868
and I was walking down
the middle of the street, proud, defiant.

529
00:44:44,683 --> 00:44:46,617
[No Audible Dialogue]

530
00:44:46,685 --> 00:44:49,916
Don Bachardy must have been
absolutely bowled over...

531
00:44:49,988 --> 00:44:53,355
by suddenly, through
his relationship with Isherwood,

532
00:44:53,425 --> 00:44:57,122
meeting the huge big-name people...

533
00:44:57,195 --> 00:44:59,186
<i>that were friends of Isherwood.</i>

534
00:44:59,264 --> 00:45:03,792
<i>Authors like Tennessee Williams,
Truman Capote,</i>

535
00:45:03,869 --> 00:45:06,633
<i>composers like Igor Stravinsky.</i>

536
00:45:06,705 --> 00:45:10,300
<i>And all of a sudden,
here is this very young man,</i>

537
00:45:10,375 --> 00:45:12,741
<i>thrown into social settings.</i>

538
00:45:12,811 --> 00:45:15,678
<i>It must have been
enormously intimidating.</i>

539
00:45:19,951 --> 00:45:23,114
<i>[York As Isherwood]
Floods of tears from Don this evening.</i>

540
00:45:23,188 --> 00:45:28,820
<i>Don feels left out of everything,
ignored, overlooked, slighted.</i>

541
00:45:29,895 --> 00:45:32,227
<i>And what am I to say? It's true.</i>

542
00:45:32,297 --> 00:45:38,031
<i>That's how the world treats young people,
and it hasn't changed since I was 20.</i>

543
00:45:43,608 --> 00:45:47,169
<i>[Bachardy]
I was feeling incredibly insecure.</i>

544
00:45:47,245 --> 00:45:51,511
<i>I wanted people to like me
for who I really was,</i>

545
00:45:51,583 --> 00:45:55,610
<i>but I wasn't sure myself who I was.</i>

546
00:45:59,357 --> 00:46:03,623
What would it feel like
to be 25 or 22 years old...

547
00:46:03,695 --> 00:46:07,153
and be sitting down to dinner
with Somerset Maugham
or E. M. Forster--

548
00:46:07,232 --> 00:46:09,393
<i>all of these famous people--</i>

549
00:46:09,467 --> 00:46:12,595
<i>and you're just this handsome young man?</i>

550
00:46:12,671 --> 00:46:14,662
<i>But Don did it.</i>

551
00:46:14,739 --> 00:46:17,333
<i>He experienced it, I think,
in the best way...</i>

552
00:46:17,409 --> 00:46:20,310
<i>because he listened to them,
learned from them,</i>

553
00:46:20,378 --> 00:46:22,437
<i>interacted with them...</i>

554
00:46:22,514 --> 00:46:24,812
<i>and then went home
and complained to Chris...</i>

555
00:46:24,883 --> 00:46:27,113
<i>about how he felt
and how he was treated.</i>

556
00:46:27,185 --> 00:46:30,052
<i>On the one hand, you're so flattered
that you're with these people.</i>

557
00:46:30,121 --> 00:46:34,148
<i>On the other hand,
how can they view you in your finest...</i>

558
00:46:34,225 --> 00:46:36,250
when you haven't developed
who you are yet?

559
00:46:36,328 --> 00:46:41,891
<i>♪♪ [Dramatic]
[Actor On TV]</i>

560
00:46:42,968 --> 00:46:45,732
<i>[Bachardy]
The profession that I dreamed of...</i>

561
00:46:45,804 --> 00:46:49,103
<i>when I was a kid
was being an actor,</i>

562
00:46:49,174 --> 00:46:53,611
<i>and by "actor," of course,
I meant movie star.</i>

563
00:47:00,819 --> 00:47:04,915
<i>So I was quite excited
when Chris was invited to Key West...</i>

564
00:47:04,990 --> 00:47:09,552
<i>by Tennessee Williams
for the filming of </i>The Rose Tattoo...</i>

565
00:47:09,628 --> 00:47:13,223
<i>with Anna Magnani
and Burt Lancaster.</i>

566
00:47:24,376 --> 00:47:30,337
<i>And Anna Magnani provided me, also,
with a very key experience...</i>

567
00:47:30,415 --> 00:47:33,009
<i>in regard to movie stars.</i>

568
00:47:34,085 --> 00:47:37,851
<i>She was the first movie star
and the only one...</i>

569
00:47:37,922 --> 00:47:42,450
<i>that I actually saw and heard fart.</i>

570
00:47:43,528 --> 00:47:47,794
<i>A t the tender age of 19,
I had never acknowledged...</i>

571
00:47:47,866 --> 00:47:51,597
<i>that real movie stars ever farted.</i>

572
00:47:53,371 --> 00:47:57,467
<i>I also got a part
as an extra in the movie.</i>

573
00:47:57,542 --> 00:48:00,204
<i>It's at the moment
when a little coupe...</i>

574
00:48:00,278 --> 00:48:05,181
<i>drives up to Marisa Pavan's house
to pick her up.</i>

575
00:48:05,250 --> 00:48:10,381
<i>The four people in the car
are supposed to be young friends of hers,</i>

576
00:48:10,455 --> 00:48:14,551
<i>and I was one of the two
in the backseat.</i>

577
00:48:15,527 --> 00:48:19,486
<i>It was an awful,
humiliating experience.</i>

578
00:48:19,564 --> 00:48:24,126
<i>Like all extras,
the four of us were treated like cattle.</i>

579
00:48:24,202 --> 00:48:27,035
<i>But it was a useful experience,</i>

580
00:48:27,105 --> 00:48:31,735
<i>because I never again yearned
to be a star of the cinema.</i>

581
00:48:46,391 --> 00:48:50,885
<i>The only thing that I knew
I was clearly good at was drawing people,</i>

582
00:48:50,962 --> 00:48:56,901
<i>and Chris realized very early on
that I had a flair for it.</i>

583
00:49:01,773 --> 00:49:05,607
<i>In fact, the very first drawing
I did from life was of Chris,</i>

584
00:49:05,677 --> 00:49:07,770
<i>and I still have it.</i>

585
00:49:14,786 --> 00:49:19,189
<i>He was urging me to find out
whether or not I might want to be an artist...</i>

586
00:49:20,258 --> 00:49:23,785
<i>and kept prodding me
to try art school.</i>

587
00:49:24,863 --> 00:49:28,560
<i>It was about three years
before I did, in fact, enroll...</i>

588
00:49:28,633 --> 00:49:32,034
<i>for a summer term at an art school.</i>

589
00:49:32,103 --> 00:49:35,561
<i>It was an immediate success.</i>

590
00:49:36,641 --> 00:49:40,577
<i>I was a dedicated
and inexhaustible art student...</i>

591
00:49:40,645 --> 00:49:43,443
<i>for the next four years.</i>

592
00:49:45,817 --> 00:49:49,913
<i>He was totally responsible
for my being an artist,</i>

593
00:49:49,988 --> 00:49:53,685
<i>because he not only paid
for all of my schooling,</i>

594
00:49:53,758 --> 00:49:58,718
<i>but far more importantly,
he was there when I came home...</i>

595
00:49:58,797 --> 00:50:03,131
<i>and said,
"Let me see what you did today. "</i>

596
00:50:04,135 --> 00:50:07,298
<i>And that, of course,
means more than anything.</i>

597
00:50:08,940 --> 00:50:11,033
<i>When you're doubtful
about yourself...</i>

598
00:50:11,109 --> 00:50:15,773
<i>and trying to be confident
about what you're doing,</i>

599
00:50:15,847 --> 00:50:20,875
<i>to have somebody give you
that kind of support is golden.</i>

600
00:50:22,587 --> 00:50:27,456
But my father, you know, he--
he not only never encouraged me,

601
00:50:27,525 --> 00:50:30,961
he actively tried to discourage me.

602
00:50:31,029 --> 00:50:36,433
<i>He was unreceptive
to my being an artist,</i>

603
00:50:36,501 --> 00:50:41,029
<i>made it clear
he hated my queerness.</i>

604
00:50:42,073 --> 00:50:47,010
<i>And when I came to dinner with them,
I was instructed--</i>

605
00:50:47,078 --> 00:50:52,345
<i>not by him, because he was too cowardly,
but my mother had to tell me--</i>

606
00:50:52,417 --> 00:50:54,681
<i>that Chris was not to be mentioned.</i>

607
00:50:54,752 --> 00:50:59,780
Well, I should never have agreed
to such a restriction.

608
00:50:59,858 --> 00:51:01,883
How dare they?

609
00:51:03,061 --> 00:51:04,995
Hi.
Hi. You're Dan. I'm Don.

610
00:51:05,063 --> 00:51:06,997
Great to meet you.
Pleased to meet you.

611
00:51:07,065 --> 00:51:09,226
Would you come and sit--

612
00:51:09,300 --> 00:51:11,791
<i>[Bachardy]
Once I found my vocation,</i>

613
00:51:11,870 --> 00:51:16,239
<i>I was then indefatigable;
nothing would stop me.</i>

614
00:51:16,307 --> 00:51:21,836
<i>I wouldn't take no for an answer.
I would draw anybody in any situation.</i>

615
00:51:34,459 --> 00:51:40,398
<i>In the very early weeks
of our getting to know each other,</i>

616
00:51:40,465 --> 00:51:45,198
<i>Chris took me to an Italian restaurant
on Gower Street.</i>

617
00:51:45,270 --> 00:51:48,762
<i>We were in the restaurant
about 10 minutes...</i>

618
00:51:48,840 --> 00:51:53,174
<i>when the door opened,
and in came Montgomery Clift.</i>

619
00:51:53,244 --> 00:51:57,442
I said, "Chris,
Montgomery Clift just came in."

620
00:51:57,515 --> 00:52:01,508
And I was thrilled.

621
00:52:01,586 --> 00:52:04,146
And I was watching him,

622
00:52:04,222 --> 00:52:08,659
and, um, he came closer
and closer and closer,

623
00:52:08,726 --> 00:52:14,187
until finally he was right at our table,
and he said, "Hello, Chris."

624
00:52:15,266 --> 00:52:18,463
Well, I nearly fainted.

625
00:52:19,537 --> 00:52:24,770
I had no idea.
I mean, here was this major hot star.

626
00:52:24,842 --> 00:52:28,972
And I saw him
from the very first moment he came in,

627
00:52:29,047 --> 00:52:32,505
and imagine his coming
right up to the table.

628
00:52:32,583 --> 00:52:35,279
And of course,
Chris instantly introduced me.

629
00:52:35,353 --> 00:52:38,447
Well, I was just--
[Chuckles]
undone.

630
00:52:41,292 --> 00:52:44,659
<i>And when he realized
that was a way to thrill me,</i>

631
00:52:44,729 --> 00:52:48,324
<i>he charmed every movie star we met.</i>

632
00:52:49,901 --> 00:52:51,892
<i>He would go
to all kinds of occasions...</i>

633
00:52:51,970 --> 00:52:54,939
<i>that couldn't have
interested him in the least,</i>

634
00:52:55,006 --> 00:52:59,409
<i>except that he might meet someone
who happened to be somebody...</i>

635
00:52:59,477 --> 00:53:04,608
<i>from my pantheon
of most favorite favorites.</i>

636
00:53:05,683 --> 00:53:10,245
<i>And that's the way I'd gotten
many celebrities to sit for me.</i>

637
00:54:03,474 --> 00:54:06,500
<i>If I were forced to work
from a photograph,</i>

638
00:54:06,577 --> 00:54:08,511
<i>I probably wouldn't paint.</i>

639
00:54:08,579 --> 00:54:11,878
<i>But then, if I accepted the limitation,</i>

640
00:54:11,949 --> 00:54:13,883
<i>I would choose
a very bad photograph,</i>

641
00:54:13,951 --> 00:54:18,820
<i>because at least
that would force my imagination.</i>

642
00:54:33,037 --> 00:54:36,529
<i>[York As Isherwood]
Coming back at 10:45 from supper--<i></i>

643
00:54:36,607 --> 00:54:40,703
<i>the nice smell of redwood
as I lifted the garage door...</i>

644
00:54:42,013 --> 00:54:46,575
<i>and the feeling of impotence,
or what it really amounts to:</i>

645
00:54:46,651 --> 00:54:52,419
<i>lack of inclination to cope
with a constructed, invented plot.</i>

646
00:54:52,490 --> 00:54:56,620
<i>Why not write about one's experiences
from day to day?</i>

647
00:54:56,694 --> 00:54:58,628
<i>And then, as I slid my door back,</i>

648
00:54:58,696 --> 00:55:02,860
<i>this sinking,
sick feeling of love for Don--</i>

649
00:55:02,934 --> 00:55:05,926
<i>somehow connected
with the torn shorts--</i>

650
00:55:06,003 --> 00:55:09,769
<i>and the reality of that, so far more...</i>

651
00:55:09,841 --> 00:55:12,810
<i>than all this tiresome fiction.</i>

652
00:55:12,877 --> 00:55:16,643
<i>Why invent
when life is so prodigious?</i>

653
00:55:16,714 --> 00:55:22,152
<i>Perhaps I'll never write another novel
or anything invented...</i>

654
00:55:23,221 --> 00:55:26,384
<i>except, of course, for money.</i>

655
00:56:09,767 --> 00:56:13,726
<i>[Woman]
What are you famous for?<i>
I'm a painter. I paint people.</i>

656
00:56:13,804 --> 00:56:15,772
Why don't you paint me?
<i>[Laughs]</i>

657
00:56:15,840 --> 00:56:19,071
I've got a nice face.
A good question. Yeah.

658
00:56:19,143 --> 00:56:24,103
<i>Because I only see you once a week,
and I expect you're busy.</i>

659
00:56:24,182 --> 00:56:28,516
<i>Well, yeah, but I can always
rearrange my schedule
to get painted.</i>

660
00:56:28,586 --> 00:56:30,520
Well, thank you very much.
<i>Thank you.</i>

661
00:56:30,588 --> 00:56:32,579
Have a good one.

662
00:56:41,699 --> 00:56:43,894
<i>Hi, Don.</i>
Hi.</i>

663
00:56:43,968 --> 00:56:45,959
<i>[Bachardy]
My first one-man show...</i>

664
00:56:46,037 --> 00:56:49,939
<i>was in October of 1961 in London...</i>

665
00:56:50,007 --> 00:56:52,669
<i>at the Redfern Gallery.</i>

666
00:56:52,743 --> 00:56:57,305
This was my official introduction...

667
00:56:57,381 --> 00:57:00,373
to my identity as an artist.

668
00:57:04,889 --> 00:57:08,689
<i>[York As Isherwood]
I'm so proud of Don sometimes
that I could burst.</i>

669
00:57:08,759 --> 00:57:11,728
<i>Don was interviewed
and photographed by the press,</i>

670
00:57:11,796 --> 00:57:15,823
<i>while I kept away in a corner,
nearly splitting with pride.</i>

671
00:57:17,868 --> 00:57:23,773
<i>I put on a rather disparaging expression,
like a parent who fears to show his pride.</i>

672
00:57:24,775 --> 00:57:29,235
<i>Of course, I know it's the most
monstrous egotism on my part to be proud,</i>

673
00:57:29,313 --> 00:57:32,976
<i>to claim any part
of what he has made of himself.</i>

674
00:57:33,985 --> 00:57:37,113
<i>Just the same, I do.</i>

675
00:57:38,656 --> 00:57:41,750
<i>[Bachardy]
He often said he'd never been denied...</i>

676
00:57:41,826 --> 00:57:45,887
<i>any of the pleasures
and satisfactions of a parent,</i>

677
00:57:45,963 --> 00:57:47,897
<i>because he'd met me...</i>

678
00:57:47,965 --> 00:57:50,798
when I was young enough
that he could still have...

679
00:57:50,868 --> 00:57:54,463
an enormous influence on my development,

680
00:57:54,538 --> 00:57:58,304
and this was
a crowning achievement.

681
00:58:01,412 --> 00:58:05,940
Like this?
If I could--And--

682
00:58:06,017 --> 00:58:08,076
Yeah, I'm flexible,
you know.

683
00:58:08,152 --> 00:58:11,144
<i>I had finally
established myself as an artist.</i>

684
00:58:11,222 --> 00:58:17,058
<i>I had my own persona, as it were,
and I could function independently.</i>

685
00:58:17,128 --> 00:58:21,224
<i>The question was,
did I want to go on with the old life--</i>

686
00:58:21,299 --> 00:58:23,267
<i>which had brought me to this point--</i>

687
00:58:23,334 --> 00:58:26,633
<i>or did I want to go on to fresher fields?</i>

688
00:58:30,641 --> 00:58:35,237
<i>The thought crossed my mind
that I might think of leaving Chris.</i>

689
00:58:39,183 --> 00:58:45,122
All kinds of very real problems
between us...

690
00:58:45,189 --> 00:58:49,956
could be so effectively dealt with...

691
00:58:50,027 --> 00:58:52,188
in our animal personas.

692
00:58:52,263 --> 00:58:55,096
<i>Because I could give voice...</i>

693
00:58:55,166 --> 00:58:57,532
<i>to my feelings--
[Meowing]</i>

694
00:58:57,601 --> 00:59:00,764
<i>of being deprived
of this or that experience...</i>

695
00:59:00,838 --> 00:59:03,329
<i>because of my life with Chris--</i>

696
00:59:03,407 --> 00:59:06,535
<i>my life with somebody
so much older than myself--</i>

697
00:59:09,080 --> 00:59:12,982
<i>[Meows]
I could voice it in terms
of a poor little kitten...</i>

698
00:59:13,050 --> 00:59:17,180
<i>struggling against
insurmountable odds,</i>

699
00:59:17,254 --> 00:59:20,121
<i>and how brave that little cat was,</i>

700
00:59:20,191 --> 00:59:22,216
<i>and how dear and deep his love...</i>

701
00:59:22,293 --> 00:59:26,559
<i>that, despite everything
that he was giving up,</i>

702
00:59:26,630 --> 00:59:29,565
<i>he could still take care
of that old horse.</i>

703
00:59:34,338 --> 00:59:38,604
<i>Chris had been open with me
about his past--</i>

704
00:59:38,642 --> 00:59:43,409
<i>all his lovers,
all his adventures.</i>

705
00:59:43,481 --> 00:59:46,211
<i>I took the obvious position:</i>

706
00:59:46,283 --> 00:59:49,252
"Well, how can you deny me...

707
00:59:49,320 --> 00:59:53,154
such adventures, such freedom?"

708
00:59:53,224 --> 00:59:57,024
<i>[Man Singing Rhythm And Blues]
♪ Hello there, hi ♪</i>

709
00:59:57,094 --> 01:00:01,997
<i>♪ You know you really turn me on ♪♪
I would go out "mousing. "
That was the term we used for it.</i>

710
01:00:03,067 --> 01:00:07,436
<i>Next morning-- or that night
when I came home, if he was still up--</i>

711
01:00:07,505 --> 01:00:11,066
<i>he would ask me,
"How was the mouse tonight?"</i>

712
01:00:11,142 --> 01:00:13,610
<i>And I'd say, "Plump one,"</i>

713
01:00:13,677 --> 01:00:17,408
<i>or, "A disappointingly skinny one. "</i>

714
01:00:18,416 --> 01:00:22,978
And I also insisted
that he have his affairs too,

715
01:00:23,053 --> 01:00:27,114
just because I didn't want
to always feel like the guilty one.

716
01:00:28,659 --> 01:00:33,756
<i>I didn't like it so much
when he found really quite attractive,</i>

717
01:00:33,831 --> 01:00:35,765
intelligent people.

718
01:00:35,833 --> 01:00:40,827
That wasn't quite what I had in mind.
[Laughing]

719
01:00:40,905 --> 01:00:45,399
I suppose I imagined his choosing
somebody of his own age,

720
01:00:45,476 --> 01:00:48,309
which was, of course, out of the question.

721
01:00:48,379 --> 01:00:52,247
<i>[Freeman]
They tried to set rules, I think,
and tried to be pretty true to those.</i>

722
01:00:52,316 --> 01:00:56,252
<i>But Chris did not like it
if Don didn't spend the night at their house.</i>

723
01:00:56,320 --> 01:00:58,254
And he didn't like the secrecy,

724
01:00:58,322 --> 01:01:01,416
and so I think he was
more interested in disclosure--

725
01:01:01,492 --> 01:01:03,483
you know, who's doing what
and with whom.

726
01:01:05,429 --> 01:01:07,954
I'm going to stop this.
Thank you very much.

727
01:01:12,102 --> 01:01:17,540
Oh, the eyes are intense in that one.
That's a good one.

728
01:01:19,343 --> 01:01:25,077
Did I forget your ears,
or could I not see them?
I don't know. Let's see.

729
01:01:26,150 --> 01:01:29,278
I forgot them. Just--

730
01:01:39,230 --> 01:01:44,759
<i>[Bachardy]
1962, 1963 was our bumpiest period.</i>

731
01:01:47,071 --> 01:01:50,939
And that's really what prompted him...

732
01:01:51,008 --> 01:01:53,738
<i>to write</i> A Single Man,</i>

733
01:01:53,811 --> 01:01:59,374
<i>which is all based on the supposition
of a man of his age...</i>

734
01:01:59,450 --> 01:02:05,320
<i>losing his lover in an automobile accident,
and what does he do?</i>

735
01:02:05,389 --> 01:02:09,257
<i>And Chris was seriously contemplating...</i>

736
01:02:09,326 --> 01:02:14,059
<i>what kind of life he would lead
without me.</i>

737
01:02:14,131 --> 01:02:18,932
<i>I got involved with somebody, sort of.</i>

738
01:02:19,937 --> 01:02:25,500
<i>I thought maybe I might even want
to break it up with Chris. I--</i>

739
01:02:25,576 --> 01:02:27,874
<i>It made Chris miserable to know...</i>

740
01:02:27,945 --> 01:02:33,884
<i>that I was pondering such a decision.</i>

741
01:02:38,756 --> 01:02:43,284
<i>He went away to San Francisco
to teach up there...</i>

742
01:02:43,360 --> 01:02:46,090
<i>for, oh, at least a couple of months.</i>

743
01:02:46,163 --> 01:02:48,131
<i>And I was in the house alone here,</i>

744
01:02:48,198 --> 01:02:51,167
<i>and it wasn't really any better.</i>

745
01:03:00,177 --> 01:03:06,116
<i>"Dear Horse,
Old Cat is coming out of a deep sulk,</i>

746
01:03:06,183 --> 01:03:10,483
<i>"one that any horse
would thank his stars for having missed.</i>

747
01:03:11,555 --> 01:03:16,288
<i>I need you terribly sometimes.
It shocks me how much. "</i>

748
01:03:16,360 --> 01:03:18,760
[Whinnies]
<i>"I don't want to need you.</i>

749
01:03:18,829 --> 01:03:21,855
<i>"I want to be able to rely on myself.</i>

750
01:03:21,932 --> 01:03:25,197
<i>"I don't like depressing you with all my woes.</i>

751
01:03:26,670 --> 01:03:28,638
<i>"I must do this alone.</i>

752
01:03:28,706 --> 01:03:30,799
<i>"I must get through by myself.</i>

753
01:03:30,874 --> 01:03:35,106
<i>"And I try hard to love you
instead of just needing you.</i>

754
01:03:36,714 --> 01:03:40,309
<i>Your Overwrought Pussy. "<i></i>

755
01:03:44,722 --> 01:03:48,681
<i>[Bucknell]
Don felt a huge obligation to Isherwood...</i>

756
01:03:48,759 --> 01:03:52,752
<i>that was almost unbearable--
that he'd been given so much.</i>

757
01:03:52,830 --> 01:03:55,492
<i>At one time he said,
"I want to get really rich...</i>

758
01:03:55,566 --> 01:03:58,399
<i>"so that I can no longer
be beholden to you...</i>

759
01:03:58,469 --> 01:04:00,403
<i>and I can somehow pay it back. "</i>

760
01:04:00,471 --> 01:04:03,838
<i>And freedom is just not necessarily
being given everything.</i>

761
01:04:03,907 --> 01:04:06,467
Freedom is something
you need to get for yourself.

762
01:04:06,543 --> 01:04:11,480
<i>Isherwood by then was
a mature and experienced person...</i>

763
01:04:11,548 --> 01:04:17,180
<i>who used every ounce
of his self-control and knowledge...</i>

764
01:04:17,254 --> 01:04:22,248
not to allow
this thing to break altogether.

765
01:04:31,101 --> 01:04:34,366
<i>[York As Isherwood]
Own Sweetest Fur,</i>

766
01:04:34,438 --> 01:04:36,736
got the dear letter yesterday.

767
01:04:36,807 --> 01:04:41,767
<i>I do hope Black Puss
will scat for a while and let you work.</i>

768
01:04:42,846 --> 01:04:46,373
<i>The Bay is significantly beautiful.</i>

769
01:04:46,450 --> 01:04:49,544
<i>I lie on the roof when I can
and sun.</i>

770
01:04:49,620 --> 01:04:52,885
<i>Also, I walk all over the area,</i>

771
01:04:52,956 --> 01:04:56,289
<i>and I'm learning its geography at last.</i>

772
01:04:57,561 --> 01:05:01,691
<i>Kitty would have clapped his paws
and laughed from the bottom of his furry heart...</i>

773
01:05:01,765 --> 01:05:04,461
<i>to see Drub hopelessly stuck...</i>

774
01:05:04,535 --> 01:05:08,062
<i>on a vertical bit of Jones Street
high up on Russian Hill...</i>

775
01:05:08,138 --> 01:05:13,201
<i>and trying to cling
to the passing houses with his hooves.</i>

776
01:05:14,278 --> 01:05:18,908
<i>Think of his dear so very much,
and sends thoughts of love...</i>

777
01:05:18,982 --> 01:05:23,248
<i>and prays that Kitty
will find a way out of his sadness.</i>

778
01:05:25,422 --> 01:05:27,356
<i>[Bachardy]
I adored his drawings...</i>

779
01:05:27,424 --> 01:05:32,361
<i>because he had absolutely
no technical skill whatsoever,</i>

780
01:05:32,429 --> 01:05:34,659
<i>and that made them
all the more wonderful.</i>

781
01:05:34,732 --> 01:05:37,496
[Chuckling]

782
01:05:37,568 --> 01:05:40,765
<i>Yes, and they made me cry.</i>

783
01:05:49,179 --> 01:05:55,084
<i>Of course, the effect of Chris's
leaving the house for three months...</i>

784
01:05:55,152 --> 01:06:00,590
<i>was that it immediately put
the other relationship into perspective,</i>

785
01:06:00,657 --> 01:06:04,115
<i>and I realized
I wasn't nearly as involved...</i>

786
01:06:04,194 --> 01:06:07,095
<i>as maybe I thought I was.</i>

787
01:06:20,878 --> 01:06:23,108
<i>[Bucknell]
We have, in this record of the diaries,</i>

788
01:06:23,180 --> 01:06:27,981
<i>the true account of how bad
and how good a relationship can be.</i>

789
01:06:29,787 --> 01:06:34,884
<i>I came across a passage
in the 1967 diary.</i>

790
01:06:34,958 --> 01:06:39,224
<i>He's writing about
how could love be profane...</i>

791
01:06:39,296 --> 01:06:41,423
<i>if it was really love.</i>

792
01:06:41,498 --> 01:06:44,399
<i>He talks about that idea
of sacred and profane love...</i>

793
01:06:44,468 --> 01:06:47,494
<i>and then observes
that Don has become...</i>

794
01:06:47,571 --> 01:06:51,473
<i>his path to spiritual enlightenment.</i>

795
01:07:22,873 --> 01:07:25,865
Chris and Don were never apologetic
about being a couple,

796
01:07:26,243 --> 01:07:28,438
and there were lots of reasons
that they could have been--

797
01:07:28,512 --> 01:07:31,913
<i>the age difference thing,
the difference in status...</i>

798
01:07:31,982 --> 01:07:35,918
<i>at the beginning
of their relationship, in particular--
but they never were.</i>

799
01:07:35,986 --> 01:07:39,285
<i>They would go to Hollywood parties
when closeted people
were surrounding them,</i>

800
01:07:39,356 --> 01:07:41,290
<i>and they were a couple.</i>

801
01:07:42,526 --> 01:07:47,327
<i>[Bachardy]
Joseph Cotten was very rude to me
in front of a lot of people...</i>

802
01:07:47,397 --> 01:07:51,697
<i>at a party
at David and Jennifer Selznick's.</i>

803
01:07:51,768 --> 01:07:55,636
He talked in a loud voice
about "half men"...

804
01:07:55,706 --> 01:07:58,038
and how disgusting they were.

805
01:07:58,108 --> 01:08:03,410
<i>He wouldn't dare talk like that
within earshot of Chris.</i>

806
01:08:03,480 --> 01:08:08,008
<i>He would pick a moment
when I was by myself.</i>

807
01:08:09,553 --> 01:08:15,150
<i>Even the homophobes could usually
bring themselves to be polite to Chris,</i>

808
01:08:15,225 --> 01:08:18,194
<i>because they knew
he was a distinguished writer.</i>

809
01:08:18,262 --> 01:08:23,222
<i>But who was I? I was just this little
upstart faggot from their point of view.</i>

810
01:08:23,300 --> 01:08:27,168
<i>[Freeman]
They were friends
with Anthony Perkins, the star of Psycho,</i>

811
01:08:27,237 --> 01:08:29,364
<i>who wrestled and struggled
with his sexuality all his life...</i>

812
01:08:29,439 --> 01:08:31,999
<i>and who, of course,
died of AIDS complications.</i>

813
01:08:32,075 --> 01:08:34,066
<i>He would come
to Chris and Don's house,</i>

814
01:08:34,144 --> 01:08:37,375
having just spent the entire day in therapy
trying to not be gay.

815
01:08:37,447 --> 01:08:40,177
And I think they looked upon that
with much sadness,

816
01:08:40,250 --> 01:08:42,275
because they were
so comfortable in their lives.

817
01:08:42,352 --> 01:08:47,016
<i>Christopher never took a woman
with him to a function
so that it would appear he was straight.</i>

818
01:08:47,090 --> 01:08:51,117
<i>Don never did.
They went to parties together.
They went as a couple,</i>

819
01:08:51,194 --> 01:08:55,597
<i>and there would be men
that they had had sex with
in the room with their wives.</i>

820
01:09:13,050 --> 01:09:16,952
<i>[Bucknell]
Part of Isherwood's
whole endeavor as a novelist...</i>

821
01:09:17,020 --> 01:09:21,457
involved emerging from the "closet,"
for want of a better word.

822
01:09:21,525 --> 01:09:25,393
<i>There are obviously
some homosexual characters
in his early books,</i>

823
01:09:25,462 --> 01:09:31,298
<i>but there's always a kind
of covertness and a coded quality
to how he talks about it.</i>

824
01:09:32,302 --> 01:09:34,236
For example, in The Berlin Stories,

825
01:09:34,304 --> 01:09:36,534
if you read it very, very carefully,

826
01:09:36,606 --> 01:09:41,134
you can pretty much guess
that the narrator, the protagonist, is gay.

827
01:09:41,211 --> 01:09:45,910
<i>But you don't know that.
It's not a big thing in the story.</i>

828
01:09:45,983 --> 01:09:49,578
<i>And as Isherwood remarked later on,
he didn't dare make it a big thing,</i>

829
01:09:49,653 --> 01:09:52,520
<i>because if he had,
it would have been the whole story.</i>

830
01:09:52,589 --> 01:09:58,050
I t was very i mportant that this observer
should have been rather sexless--

831
01:09:58,128 --> 01:10:01,188
at least how it seemed
to me at that time:

832
01:10:01,264 --> 01:10:04,927
rather unobtrusive,

833
01:10:05,002 --> 01:10:08,631
just a kind of a straight man to take--
I mean no pun here--

834
01:10:08,705 --> 01:10:13,802
a straight man to take the-- to pick up
the other people's jokes, you know?

835
01:10:13,877 --> 01:10:18,507
Later he told that story--
the story of a gay man in Berlin,
openly gay--

836
01:10:18,582 --> 01:10:20,880
he told that story
in Christopher and His Kind.

837
01:10:28,225 --> 01:10:30,659
<i>[Isherwood]
"Christopher had taken longer than Wystan...</i>

838
01:10:30,727 --> 01:10:33,696
<i>"to become aware
of his own change of attitude...</i>

839
01:10:33,764 --> 01:10:37,666
<i>"because he was embarrassed
by its basic cause:</i>

840
01:10:37,734 --> 01:10:39,793
<i>"his homosexuality.</i>

841
01:10:40,804 --> 01:10:43,773
<i>"As a homosexual, he had been wavering...</i>

842
01:10:43,840 --> 01:10:46,900
<i>"between embarrassment and defiance.</i>

843
01:10:46,977 --> 01:10:50,174
<i>"He became embarrassed
when he felt that he was making...</i>

844
01:10:50,247 --> 01:10:54,240
<i>"a selfish demand
for his individual rights...</i>

845
01:10:54,317 --> 01:10:57,582
<i>"at a time
